## Authentication

All API requests require authentication via an API key or OAuth 2.0 bearer token. Include your credentials in the `Authorization` header.

**API Key Authentication**

```http
# Include in every request header
Authorization: Bearer YOUR_API_KEY

# Or as a query parameter (not recommended for production)
GET /v3/rates/mortgage?api_key=YOUR_API_KEY
```

**OAuth 2.0 Flow**

```bash
# Step 1: Request an access token
curl -X POST "https://auth.bankrate.com/oauth/token" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded" \
  -d "grant_type=client_credentials" \
  -d "client_id=YOUR_CLIENT_ID" \
  -d "client_secret=YOUR_CLIENT_SECRET"

# Step 2: Use the token in subsequent requests
curl -X GET "https://api.bankrate.com/v3/rates/mortgage" \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer ACCESS_TOKEN"
```

::alert
---
appearance: "warning"
show-icon: true
title: "Key rotation best practices"
---
Rotate your API keys every 90 days. Use environment variables to store keys and never commit them to source control.
::

